============================================================
PROBLEM 1: MONTY HALL - SOBER AND DIZZY
============================================================

------------------------------------------------------------
PART (a): SOBER MONTY
------------------------------------------------------------

Sober Monty knows where the car is:
- If car is behind A (contestant's choice), Monty randomly opens B or C
- If car is behind B, Monty must open C (can't reveal car)
- If car is behind C, Monty must open B (can't reveal car)

Data: Monty opens door B, showing a goat

Bayes Table (Sober Monty):
--------------------------------------------------
Hypothesis   Prior      Likelihood   Prior×Lik   
--------------------------------------------------
H_A          1/3        1/2          1/6         
H_B          1/3        0            0           
H_C          1/3        1            1/3         
--------------------------------------------------
Total                                1/2         

Posterior Probabilities:
P(H_A | data) = 1/6 / 1/2 = 1/3 = 0.3333
P(H_B | data) = 0 / 1/2 = 0 = 0.0000
P(H_C | data) = 1/3 / 1/2 = 2/3 = 0.6667

Conclusion: P(car behind C) = 2/3 = 0.6667
           P(car behind A) = 1/3 = 0.3333
Best strategy: SWITCH (to door C)

------------------------------------------------------------
PART (b): DIZZY MONTY
------------------------------------------------------------

Dizzy Monty doesn't know where the car is:
- He randomly opens one of the two doors not chosen by contestant
- He might accidentally reveal the car

Data: Monty opens door B, showing a goat

Bayes Table (Dizzy Monty):
--------------------------------------------------
Hypothesis   Prior      Likelihood   Prior×Lik   
--------------------------------------------------
H_A          1/3        1/2          1/6         
H_B          1/3        0            0           
H_C          1/3        1/2          1/6         
--------------------------------------------------
Total                                1/3         

Posterior Probabilities:
P(H_A | data) = 1/6 / 1/3 = 1/2 = 0.5000
P(H_B | data) = 0 / 1/3 = 0 = 0.0000
P(H_C | data) = 1/6 / 1/3 = 1/2 = 0.5000

Conclusion: P(car behind A) = P(car behind C) = 1/2 = 0.5000
Best strategy: INDIFFERENT (switching doesn't help)

------------------------------------------------------------
PART (c): UNCERTAIN MONTY (P(sober)=0.7, P(dizzy)=0.3)
------------------------------------------------------------

Combined Likelihoods:
P(data | H_A) = 0.7 × 1/2 + 0.3 × 1/2 = 1/2 = 0.5000
P(data | H_B) = 0.7 × 0 + 0.3 × 0 = 0 = 0.0000
P(data | H_C) = 0.7 × 1 + 0.3 × 1/2 = 17/20 = 0.8500

Bayes Table (Uncertain Monty):
--------------------------------------------------
Hypothesis   Prior      Likelihood   Prior×Lik   
--------------------------------------------------
H_A          1/3        1/2          1/6         
H_B          1/3        0            0           
H_C          1/3        17/20        17/60       
--------------------------------------------------
Total                                9/20        

Posterior Probabilities:
P(H_A | data) = 1/6 / 9/20 = 10/27 = 0.3704
P(H_B | data) = 0 / 9/20 = 0 = 0.0000
P(H_C | data) = 17/60 / 9/20 = 17/27 = 0.6296

Conclusion: P(car behind C) = 17/27 = 0.6296
           P(car behind A) = 10/27 = 0.3704
Best strategy: SWITCH (to door C)

============================================================
VERIFICATION
============================================================
Sober: Sum of posteriors = 1 (check: True)
Dizzy: Sum of posteriors = 1 (check: True)
Combined: Sum of posteriors = 1 (check: True)

All computations verified with exact fractions.
